          "body": "From verse 11 onward, the chapter's tone escalates dramatically. Job will not restrain his mouth — this is a deliberate decision, not an emotional outburst, grounded in the logic of verses 7-10. His complaint takes two forms. The first is existential: God has made every refuge unavailable. The bed that should comfort instead brings terrifying dreams and visions (vv.13-14), so that Job's soul prefers strangling to his pains (machanaq, v.15 — one of the Bible's most explicit expressions of suicidal ideation, placed without editorial condemnation in canonical Scripture). The second form is theological: Job inverts Psalm 8's doxology. 'What is man that You magnify him?' echoes 'What is man that You are mindful of him?' (Psalm 8:4) — but where Psalm 8 marvels at divine condescension in grace, Job marvels at divine attention as a form of crushing surveillance. Every morning, every moment, God examines and tries him (vv.17-18). He cannot swallow his own spittle without being watched (v.19, a striking hyperbole for the absence of any private moment). God is addressed as natsar — the watcher (v.20), a title whose Hebrew root can mean both guardian and spy. Job uses it as the latter."
